column20: CONSENT TO PARTICIPATE IN RESEARCHHow Artificial Intelligence Constructs Human Preferences Through a Chat Conversation Research in Collaboration with NYU Artificial Intelligence Research (NYUAIR) IntroductionMy name is Minah Jung. I am an assistant professor of marketing at New York University, the Leonard N. Stern School of Business.  I would like to invite you to take part in our research study that explores how people learn about preferences of others when having conversations with others in a chat room setting.  PurposeThe purpose of this research study is to understand how artificial intelligence understands people劌製 preferences through a chat room.  ProceduresIn this study, you will be asked to communicate with artificial intelligence who will engage in chat conversations about your preferences in a chat room setting. If you agree to participate in this study, you will be asked to communicate with Artificial Intelligence about your preferences on cultural consumption (e.g., movies, music, and food) via an online chat room for about 20-30 minutes. After the chat, you will be asked to complete a short survey about your chat conversation and other demographic information. This research is in collaboration with the NYU Artificial Intelligence Research (NYUAIR).  Study timeThe total duration of this study is about 30 minutes.  Risk/Discomfort-There is minimal risk to you from taking part in this research. The only risk to you from participating is the possibility that some of the tasks may make you feel a bit uncomfortable. You may discontinue participation or decline to answer any questions at any time. -Breach of confidentiality: As with all research, there is a chance that confidentiality could be compromised; however, we are taking precautions to minimize this risk. Benefits There are no direct benefits to you from this research.  ConfidentialityYour study data will be handled as confidentially as possible. If results of this study are published or presented, individual names and other personally identifiable information will not be used.To minimize the risks to confidentiality, we will do the following:-               Your identity and data will not be linked.-               Your research records will be stored on password-protected office computers.-               Only I will have access to your study records.-               Your personal information may be given out if required by law. We will keep your study data as confidential as possible, unless it is certain information that we must report for legal or ethical reasons, such as abuse or intent to hurt yourself or others.Future use of study data The research data will be maintained for at least 3 years for possible use in future research by myself.  The same measures described above will be taken to protect confidentiality of this study data.  Compensation/PaymentYour participation in this study is voluntary. Participants who complete this survey will receive $3.00 for completing it. If you are not able to complete the study (e.g., technical issues), you will still be paid $0.05. To verify completion, you must enter the code found at the end of this survey into the website. If you withdraw before the end of the study, your account will not be credited. There is no cost to participate. You have the right not to answer any question you prefer not to.  RightsParticipation in research is completely voluntary.You have the right to decline to participate or to withdraw at any point in this study without penalty or loss of benefits to which you are otherwise entitled.  QuestionsIf you have any questions or concerns about this study, you may contact Minah Jung at (212) 998-0574 or minah.jung@stern.nyu.edu. For questions about your rights as a research participant, you may contact the University Committee on Activities Involving Human Subjects, 665 Broadway, Suite 804, New York, NY 10012, 212-998-4808 or ask.humansubjects@nyu.edu. Consent If you agree to take part in the research and allow Minah Jung to continue use the data for her research, please select an appropriate choice below.   YOU MUST BE 18 YEARS OR OLDER TO COMPLETE THIS STUDY.

column94: Most modern theories of decision making recognize the fact that decisions do not take place in a vacuum.  Individual preferences and knowledge, along with situational variables can greatly impact the decision process.  In order to facilitate our research on decision-making we are interested in knowing certain factors about you, the decision maker. Specifically, we are interested in whether you actually take the time to read the direction; if not, then some of our manipulations that rely on changes in the instructions will be ineffective. So, in order to demonstrate that you have read the instructions, please ignore the question about your occupation below. Instead, simply type astronomer to proceed to the next screen. Thank you very much.  What is your occupation?
column95: Debriefing Form In the beginning of this study, we told you that youwould be participating in a study about understanding how human preferences areconstructed and communicated and that you would be communicating with a personwho tries to understand your preferences by communicating with you. Our researchactually focuses on howpeople perceive human vs. non-human interaction and their experience non-humaninteractions with non-human entities (e.g., A.I.).  Although there has been a rapid increase inadoption of A.I. in our daily lives, there is little research on how peopleperceive their interactions with A.I. and their experience relative to theirinteractions with humans.  In this study, we attempt tobetter understand the underlying psychology in human vs. non-humaninteractions.   Totry and obtain unbiased or naturalreactions, we told you that your partner is a person who tries to understandyour preferences even though you interacted with an experimenter.  Unlike your case, some participants in thisstudy were told that they would be interacting with A.I. instead of aperson.   Thiswas necessary for us to betterunderstand how people劌製 belief about the ability of A.I. vs. human in accessingtheir preferences. By telling youthat your partner was an experimenter, we could not have made reliableinferences.  Without telling you thatyour partner was an experimenter, we were able to set up a wellcounter-balanced study we can analyze and infer the results concretely. We apologize for misleading you, but we believe this was the only way to examine the processesthat are the object of our research. In designing this study, we took care to minimize any possible risks or discomfortsthat might be related to the deception. Now that youunderstand the true nature of our study, you havethe chance to refuse the use of the data we collected from youfor research purposes. You are free to ask us not to use your data in our study analysis. If youdecline to let us use your data, youwill still keep your paymentjust as you would if we use your datain our analysis. This is entirelyvoluntary, butwe hope to analyze as muchdata as possible to betterunderstand the processes by whichstatus hierarchies develop in groups. Because this experiment is ongoing, werequest that you not share the true nature and purpose of thisexperiment with others who might potentially participate in our study. If you have any questions or concernsabout this study, you may contact Minah Jung at (212) 998-0510 or minah.jung@stern.nyu.edu. For questions about your rights as a researchparticipant, you may contact the University Committee on Activities InvolvingHuman Subjects, 665 Broadway, Suite 804, New York, NY 10012, 212-998-4808 or ask.humansubjects@nyu.edu. Youmaykeep this debriefing form for your future reference. Thank you againfor your participation in our research!
